relationships.description: Wet well control system includes a pump control unit
Pump control unit controls and monitors multiple pumps
Each pump is equipped with a moisture sensor
Pump control unit uses float switches to decide pump start/stop
Pump control unit receives seal failure notifications from moisture sensors
Pump control unit monitors access door sensor for unauthorized entry
Pump control unit sends operational and alarm data to the display panel
Wet well control system uses the display panel for local operation and observation
Wet well control system triggers the alarm system
Alarm system includes a buzzer for audible alerts
Control panel displays alarm status and can activate the alarm

domain_model.plantuml:
@startuml
class WetWellControlSystem {
  +monitorLiquidLevel(): void
  +reportLiquidLevel(): void
  +monitorPumpState(): void
  +reportPumpState(): void
  +provideAutomatedOperation(): void
  +provideLocalManualOverrideOperation(): void
  +provideLocalObservationalOperation(): void
  +monitorEnvironmentalConditions(): void
  +monitorTrespass(): void
  +activateAlarm(): void
}
class PumpControlUnit {
  +startPumpMotor(pump: Pump): void
  +stopPumpMotor(pump: Pump): void
  +trackMotorRunningState(): void
  +trackMotorAvailability(): void
  +equalizeRunTimes(): void
  +useLevelSwitches(): void
  +notifyMoistureDetected(sensor: MoistureSensor): void
  +handleOverheat(pump: Pump): void
  +monitorPumpingSite(): void
  +recordOperationalParameters(): void
  +provideAlarmFeature(): void
}
class Pump {
  -isRunning: boolean
  -isAvailable: boolean
  -hasSealFailure: boolean
  -hasHighTemperatureFailure: boolean
  +turnOn(): void
  +turnOff(): void
  +setAlarmState(): void
}
class MoistureSensor {
  -sealFailureDetected: boolean
  +detectSealFailure(): boolean
}
class FloatSwitch {
  -leadPumpDepth: float
  -lagPumpDepth: float
  -highLiquidDepth: float
  -state: boolean
  +detectDepth(currentDepth: float): boolean
}
class AccessDoorSensor {
  -circuitBroken: boolean
  +detectProhibitedEntry(): boolean
}
class ControlDisplayPanel {
  -pumpRunningIndicator: boolean
  -sealFailureIndicator: boolean
  -highTempIndicator: boolean
  -highLevelAlarmIndicator: boolean
  -liquidDepth: float
  +enableIndicatorLights(): void
}
class Alarm {
  +activate(): void
}
class Buzzer {
  +sound(): void
}
WetWellControlSystem *-- PumpControlUnit
PumpControlUnit --> Pump
Pump *-- MoistureSensor
PumpControlUnit --> FloatSwitch
PumpControlUnit --> MoistureSensor
PumpControlUnit --> AccessDoorSensor
PumpControlUnit --> ControlDisplayPanel
WetWellControlSystem --> ControlDisplayPanel
WetWellControlSystem *-- Alarm
Alarm *-- Buzzer
ControlDisplayPanel --> Alarm
@enduml

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The design of the wet well control system shall provide for the safety and protection of pumping station operators, maintenance personnel, and the public from hazards that may result from its operation.

issues.description: The requirement is too broad and lacks specific details on what constitutes 'safety and protection' and which hazards are to be mitigated. It does not specify hazard scenarios, safety levels, or mechanisms required (e.g., interlocks, emergency shutdown) or measurable safety criteria.
issues.suggested_fix: Specify the hazards (e.g., electrical, mechanical, environmental) and the measures to mitigate them (e.g., alarms, automatic shutdowns); define specific hazard scenarios, safety mechanisms, and measurable safety criteria.

issues.description: No acceptance criteria or test procedures are defined to verify that the system actually provides safety and protection.
issues.suggested_fix: Specify verifiable safety tests, such as response times for emergency shutdown or alarm activation under fault conditions.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The control system shall be responsible for monitoring and reporting the level of liquid in the wet well.

issues.description: 'Reporting' is not defined: it is unclear where, how often, and in what format the liquid level should be reported.
issues.suggested_fix: Specify reporting targets (e.g., local HMI, SCADA), intervals or event-driven criteria, and data format or precision.

issues.description: Without defined reporting intervals and targets, there is no way to verify compliance.
issues.suggested_fix: Define measurable reporting criteria such as update frequency and acceptable latency.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The control system shall be responsible for monitoring and reporting the state of each pump and whether it is currently running or not.

issues.description: The phrases 'state of each pump' and 'whether it is currently running or not' overlap and cause confusion about what exactly is monitored.
issues.suggested_fix: Clarify the set of pump states (e.g., Running, Stopped, Faulted) and use consistent terminology.

issues.description: The requirement does not specify monitoring intervals or the reporting mechanism.
issues.suggested_fix: Define monitoring frequency and reporting destination (e.g., push updates to display panel every 1 second).

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The control system shall activate a visual and audible alarm when a hazardous condition exists.

issues.description: The term 'hazardous condition' is not enumerated; it is unclear which events should trigger alarms.
issues.suggested_fix: List specific conditions (e.g., high liquid level, seal failure, unauthorized entry) that must cause alarm activation.

issues.description: Without defined trigger conditions and thresholds, alarm activation cannot be verified.
issues.suggested_fix: Specify activation thresholds and corresponding test cases for each hazardous condition.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The control system shall switch each submersible pump on or off in a timely fashion depending on the level of liquid within the wet well.

issues.description: The phrase 'timely fashion' is not quantified; it is unclear what maximum delay is acceptable.
issues.suggested_fix: Specify maximum response time (e.g., pump must start or stop within 2 seconds of threshold crossing).

issues.description: No performance criteria are given to enable verification of timely actuation.
issues.suggested_fix: Define timing requirements and corresponding test procedures.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: Should a seal failure be detected, the pump shall be turned off and alarm state set.

issues.description: The reaction time to turn off the pump and set the alarm is not specified.
issues.suggested_fix: Define maximum allowable delay between moisture sensor alert and pump shutdown/alarm activation.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The wet well control system shall provide automated operation.

issues.description: The scope of 'automated operation' is not defined; it is unclear which actions are automated.
issues.suggested_fix: Specify exactly which processes (e.g., pump start/stop, alarm handling) must operate automatically.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The wet well control system shall provide local manual override operation.

issues.description: It is unclear which controls can be overridden manually and what safety interlocks remain.
issues.suggested_fix: Define allowable manual override actions and associated safety checks.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The wet well control system shall provide local observational operation.

issues.description: The term 'observational operation' is undefined; it is not clear what information must be viewable.
issues.suggested_fix: Specify which parameters and statuses must be observable locally (e.g., via display panel).

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The wet well control system shall start the pump motors to prevent the wet well from running over and stop the pump motors before the wet well runs dry.

issues.description: This requirement conflicts with REQ-026, which assigns the same responsibility to the PumpControlUnit.
issues.suggested_fix: Clarify whether the responsibility lies with the WetWellControlSystem or the PumpControlUnit, or specify collaboration between them.

issues.description: High-level ('running over') and low-level ('runs dry') thresholds are not defined in measurable units.
issues.suggested_fix: Specify numeric liquid level thresholds (e.g., feet) for pump start and stop actions.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The wet well control system shall keep track of whether or not each motor is running.

issues.description: This requirement conflicts with REQ-027, which assigns the same responsibility to the PumpControlUnit.
issues.suggested_fix: Clarify whether the responsibility lies with the WetWellControlSystem or the PumpControlUnit, or specify collaboration between them.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The wet well control system shall monitor the pumping site for unauthorized entry or trespass.

issues.description: The physical boundaries of the 'pumping site' and what constitutes unauthorized entry are not specified.
issues.suggested_fix: Define the monitored area and criteria or sensors (doors, fences, motion detectors) for trespass detection.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The wet well control system shall monitor the environmental conditions within the wet well.

issues.description: 'Environmental conditions' is too broad; specific parameters (e.g., temperature, humidity, gas concentration) are not listed.
issues.suggested_fix: List the exact environmental metrics to be monitored and their acceptable ranges.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The wet well control system shall monitor the physical condition of each pump for the existence of moisture and excessive temperatures.

issues.description: No threshold is given for 'excessive temperature' and the required temperature sensing mechanism is not defined.
issues.suggested_fix: Define temperature limits, specify sensor type or location, and integrate a TemperatureSensor requirement.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The wet well control system shall display real time and historical operational parameters.

issues.description: Operational parameters to display (e.g., flow rate, pump run time, alarm history) are not enumerated.
issues.suggested_fix: List specific parameters and display formats (charts, tables) required.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The wet well control system shall provide an alarm feature.

issues.description: This requirement overlaps with REQ-004 and is redundant.
issues.suggested_fix: Merge with REQ-004 or remove duplication to streamline alarm requirements.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: Monitor and detect prohibited entry to the wet well through the access door by way of broken electrical circuit. Both audible and visible alarms shall be activated.

issues.description: Uses term 'prohibited entry' instead of 'unauthorized entry' (REQ-013), leading to mixed terminology.
issues.suggested_fix: Use consistent terminology across requirements for entry violations.

issues.description: No test procedures or thresholds defined for circuit-break detection or alarm activation.
issues.suggested_fix: Define test cases for broken-circuit detection and verify alarm response times.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: Monitor and detect occurrence of a pump motor seal leak. If a leak has been detected, both an audible and visible alarm shall be activated.

issues.description: This duplicates REQ-007; consider consolidating seal failure detection requirements.
issues.suggested_fix: Merge duplicate requirements to avoid redundancy.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The pump control unit shall start the submersible pump motors to prevent the wet well from running over and stop the pump motors before the wet well runs dry.

issues.description: This requirement conflicts with REQ-011 (WetWellControlSystem) and duplicates functionality in REQ-005, assigning the same pump control responsibility at different system levels.
issues.suggested_fix: Clarify and separate responsibilities between the WetWellControlSystem and PumpControlUnit, or collapse into a single requirement specifying collaboration.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The pump control unit shall keep track of whether or not each motor is running.

issues.description: This requirement conflicts with REQ-012, which assigns the same responsibility to the WetWellControlSystem.
issues.suggested_fix: Clarify whether the responsibility lies with the PumpControlUnit or the WetWellControlSystem, or specify collaboration between them.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: If a pump motor is not available to run and a request has been made for the pump motor to start, an alternative motor shall be started in its place.

issues.description: Selection criteria for choosing an alternative motor are not defined.
issues.suggested_fix: Specify the algorithm or priority rules for alternative pump selection.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The pump control unit shall be responsible for displaying real time and historical operational parameters.

issues.description: Conflicts with REQ-016, which assigns display responsibility to the wet well control system.
issues.suggested_fix: Clarify which component owns the HMI display functionality.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: When the depth of liquid is equal to or greater than the lead pump depth, the float switch shall set a state which causes the first pump to turn on.

issues.description: The format and meaning of the 'state' output (boolean, code, event) are not defined.
issues.suggested_fix: Define the float switch output type (e.g., enum {LEAD_ON, OFF}) and its protocol to the control unit.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: When the depth of liquid is equal to or greater than the lag pump depth, the float switch shall set a state which causes the second pump to turn on.

issues.description: Same ambiguity as REQ-040: unstructured 'state' output specification.
issues.suggested_fix: Standardize float switch state outputs and document all possible values.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: When the depth of liquid is equal to or greater than the allowable high liquid depth, the float switch shall set an alarm state.

issues.description: Distinction between a pump-control state and an alarm state is not defined in the float switch specification.
issues.suggested_fix: Define separate output channels or enum values for alarm versus pump-control states.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The wet well control system shall equalize the run time between the pumps.

issues.description: This requirement conflicts with REQ-031, which assigns the responsibility of equalizing run times to the pump control unit.
issues.suggested_fix: Clarify whether the responsibility lies with the WetWellControlSystem or the PumpControlUnit, or specify collaboration between them.

missing_requirements.description: No requirement for monitoring methane gas concentration and alarms
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The control system shall monitor methane gas concentration within the wet well using a dedicated MethaneSensor and trigger both audible and visual alarms when the concentration exceeds a configurable safety threshold.
missing_requirements.rationale: Although a MethaneSensor is listed, no functional requirement covers detection or response. Accumulation of methane in a confined space is an explosion hazard; monitoring gas levels and generating alarms are critical safety measures.

missing_requirements.description: No requirement for automatic ventilation fan control based on hazardous conditions
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The control system shall automatically activate the VentilationFanSwitch to run the ventilation fan when methane concentration exceeds a configurable safety threshold or ambient temperature exceeds a configurable limit, and deactivate it when conditions return to safe levels.
missing_requirements.rationale: Proper ventilation is required to mitigate explosive gas buildup and extreme temperatures; without fan control, alarms alone are insufficient to protect personnel and equipment.

missing_requirements.description: No requirement for ambient temperature monitoring and high-temperature alarms
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The control system shall monitor ambient temperature within the wet well area via a TemperatureSensor and trigger a high-temperature alarm if readings exceed a configurable safe range.
missing_requirements.rationale: Extreme ambient temperatures can degrade equipment and pose safety hazards; temperature monitoring with alarms complements moisture and gas monitoring for a comprehensive environmental safety profile.

missing_requirements.description: No requirement for monitoring power source status or integration with the Power Backup System
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The control system shall monitor primary and backup power source status via the PowerBackupSystem interface and generate an alarm if primary power is lost, ensuring a safe transition and operator notification.
missing_requirements.rationale: Loss of primary power can compromise pump operation and alarms; detecting and reporting power-fail events is essential to maintain safety and continuity.

missing_requirements.description: No requirement for safe shutdown on complete power failure
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: In the event of complete primary and backup power loss, the system shall execute a safe shutdown procedure by closing all pumps, logging the event, and activating an external warning lamp or alarm panel powered by an independent source.
missing_requirements.rationale: A graceful shutdown on power loss prevents uncontrolled pump behavior and preserves system state for recovery once power is restored.

missing_requirements.description: No requirement for interfacing with the Valve Vault Control System
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The control system shall communicate with the ValveVaultControlSystem to monitor isolation valve positions and inhibit pump operation if any required isolation valve is detected closed or malfunctioning.
missing_requirements.rationale: Pumps operating against closed or improperly positioned valves can cause overpressure or equipment damage; this interface ensures safe pump interlock.

missing_requirements.description: No requirement for integration with the Sewage Grinder Unit
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The control system shall receive status and fault notifications from the SewageGrinderUnit and generate an alarm if a grinder jam or malfunction is detected, coordinating operation sequence to prevent pump-blocking debris and potential damage.
missing_requirements.rationale: Debris jams in the grinder can lead to pump blockages; early detection, alarms, and coordination prevent pump damage and system downtime.

missing_requirements.description: No requirement for periodic self-test and health monitoring of sensors and diagnostics
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The control system shall perform periodic self-tests of all connected sensors (FloatSwitch, MoistureSensor, AccessDoorSensor, MethaneSensor, TemperatureSensor) and critical components, logging failures or drift outside valid ranges and activating maintenance alerts.
missing_requirements.rationale: Sensor failures, drift, or undiagnosed component faults can lead to undetected hazards; regular diagnostics and health checks ensure system reliability and safe operation.

missing_requirements.description: No requirement for operator alarm acknowledgement, silencing, and reset
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The control system shall provide a mechanism on the ControlDisplayPanel for authorized operators to acknowledge alarms, temporarily silence audible signals while maintaining visual indicators, and reset alarm states only after hazardous conditions have been cleared.
missing_requirements.rationale: Continuous audible alarms can desensitize operators; acknowledgement and silencing functions with visual persistence allow clear tracking of hazards and prevent alarm fatigue.

missing_requirements.description: No requirement for distinct audible alarm patterns by hazard type
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The system shall use distinct audible alarm patterns via the Buzzer for different hazard types (e.g., continuous tone for high liquid level, intermittent tone for seal failure, staccato for unauthorized entry).
missing_requirements.rationale: Differentiating alarm tones helps operators quickly identify the nature of hazards without needing to read the display.

missing_requirements.description: No requirement for displaying pump availability status
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The ControlDisplayPanel shall provide a visual indicator showing each pump's availability status (available or unavailable) based on the Pump.isAvailable attribute.
missing_requirements.rationale: Operators need visibility of pump availability to understand why a pump may not have started, improving situational awareness and reducing troubleshooting time.

missing_requirements.description: No requirement for tracking and setting pump maintenance state
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The control system shall track, display, and allow authorized maintenance personnel to set the maintenance state of each pump—marking pumps as unavailable for automated operation during scheduled or unscheduled maintenance—until manually restored.
missing_requirements.rationale: Maintenance activities require safely taking pumps offline; formal maintenance states and display improve planning, prevent unintended starts, and ensure maintenance safety.

missing_requirements.description: No requirement for system initialization and shutdown procedures
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The wet well control system shall include documented procedures for system initialization and graceful shutdown, ensuring all pumps are in a safe state, alarms are properly reset, and components are correctly configured at startup and shutdown.
missing_requirements.rationale: Startup and shutdown are critical operations that ensure safety and proper functioning, yet they are not addressed in the current requirements.

missing_requirements.description: No requirement for data backup and recovery
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The wet well control system shall automatically back up operational and historical data at regular intervals and provide mechanisms for data recovery in case of system failure, ensuring data integrity and continuity.
missing_requirements.rationale: Historical operational data is critical for maintenance and regulatory compliance; backup and recovery procedures protect against data loss.

missing_requirements.description: No requirement for user authentication and role-based access control
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The system shall enforce multi-level user authentication and role-based access control on all local and remote interfaces, with at least 'operator' and 'maintenance' roles, to ensure only authorized personnel can perform sensitive operations such as manual overrides and configuration changes.
missing_requirements.rationale: Unauthorized access to pump control or configuration poses safety and security risks; explicit authentication and RBAC are essential safeguards.

missing_requirements.description: No requirement for remote SCADA communication interface
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The system shall provide a SCADA-compatible communication interface (e.g., Modbus/TCP or OPC-UA) to transmit real-time and historical data and receive control commands from a remote host.
missing_requirements.rationale: Pumping stations are typically monitored and controlled remotely; a standard protocol interface is required for integration with SCADA.

missing_requirements.description: No requirement for securing remote communications
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: All remote communications with the control system shall be secured using industry-standard authentication and encryption (e.g., TLS), preventing eavesdropping and unauthorized command injection.
missing_requirements.rationale: Unsecured communications can be intercepted or manipulated, leading to safety hazards; encryption and authentication protect data integrity and confidentiality.

missing_requirements.description: No requirement for audit-quality logging of critical events
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The system shall record timestamped, tamper-evident logs of all critical events—pump starts/stops, alarms, mode changes, manual overrides, sensor failures, and access door breaches—and retain logs for at least two years to meet regulatory compliance.
missing_requirements.rationale: Regulatory bodies require detailed audit trails; comprehensive, secure logging supports incident investigation and compliance with EPA and DEP rules.

missing_requirements.description: No requirement for regulatory compliance reporting
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The wet well control system shall generate regulatory compliance reports—incident logs, operational statistics, and maintenance records—in formats required by EPA and DEP regulations, on demand or at scheduled intervals.
missing_requirements.rationale: Business rules require compliance with EPA and DEP; explicit reporting capabilities are necessary for regulatory audits.

missing_requirements.description: No requirement for system performance under peak load
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The wet well control system shall maintain all critical functions—sensor monitoring, alarm processing, pump control—within specified performance thresholds during peak load conditions when multiple alarms are triggered simultaneously.
missing_requirements.rationale: The system must handle worst-case scenarios without degradation of critical functions to ensure safety during high-demand events.

missing_requirements.description: No requirement for pump failure escalation procedures
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The wet well control system shall implement escalating notification procedures when pump failures persist beyond a defined time threshold, including automated alerts to maintenance personnel and supervisors.
missing_requirements.rationale: Persistent or multiple pump failures require escalation to ensure timely response and prevent system downtime.

missing_requirements.description: No requirement for configuration management of threshold values
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The system shall allow authorized users to configure and update all operational thresholds—leadPumpDepth, lagPumpDepth, highLiquidDepth for FloatSwitch, as well as gas and temperature thresholds—via the ControlDisplayPanel or remote interface, with validation and audit logging of changes.
missing_requirements.rationale: Threshold values are critical to system operation; configurability and audit logging allow safe, traceable tuning for changing field conditions without code changes.

missing_requirements.description: No requirement for high availability or redundancy of the PumpControlUnit
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The system shall provide a redundant backup PumpControlUnit capable of automatically taking over control without interruption in case of primary unit failure, achieving an availability target of at least 99.9%.
missing_requirements.rationale: Continuous operation is critical to prevent sewage overflows; redundancy ensures the system remains operational despite hardware faults.

missing_requirements.description: No requirement for sensor calibration and drift detection
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The system shall support calibration procedures for all analog sensors—including FloatSwitch thresholds, MoistureSensor, MethaneSensor, and TemperatureSensor—and detect sensor drift by comparing against known references, generating calibration-due alerts.
missing_requirements.rationale: Sensors can drift over time, leading to false readings or missed alarms; calibration support and drift detection maintain measurement accuracy.

missing_requirements.description: No requirement for querying and displaying historical data on the ControlDisplayPanel
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The ControlDisplayPanel shall allow users to query and view historical operational data—pump run times, alarm events, and liquid levels—for a selected time range, with timestamps and simple graphical representations.
missing_requirements.rationale: Operators and maintenance personnel need to analyze past events for diagnostics and trend analysis; onboard historical queries improve usability.

domain_model_issues.description: The WetWellControlSystem class lacks attributes to store operational parameters and alarm states, which are required by REQ-016, REQ-017, and REQ-030.
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Add attributes such as 'operationalParameters' (list/dictionary) and 'alarmState' (boolean) to track these states.

domain_model_issues.description: The PumpControlUnit class lacks attributes to store motor availability and run times, which are required by REQ-028 and REQ-031.
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Add attributes such as 'motorAvailability' (list/dictionary) and 'runTimes' (list/dictionary) to track these states.

domain_model_issues.description: The relationship multiplicity is set as 1..* for Pump, but REQ-029 implies that there must be at least two pumps to allow for alternative motor startup.
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Update the target multiplicity to '2..*' to enforce the requirement of having at least two pumps.

domain_model_issues.description: The Alarm class lacks attributes to distinguish between different alarm types (e.g., seal failure, high temperature, high water level).
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Add an attribute 'alarmType' (enum) to differentiate between alarm conditions.

domain_model_issues.description: The ControlDisplayPanel class lacks methods and attributes to display real-time and historical operational parameters as required by REQ-016 and REQ-037.
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Add methods such as 'displayOperationalParameters(realTimeData, historicalData)' and 'displayHistoricalParameters()', and include attributes to store real-time and historical data.

domain_model_issues.description: No sensor class for detecting excessive pump temperature despite REQ-015 requiring temperature monitoring.
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Introduce a TemperatureSensor class with a detectOverheat() method and associate it with Pump and PumpControlUnit.

domain_model_issues.description: FloatSwitch.state is a single boolean but requirements REQ-040–REQ-042 require multiple distinct states (OFF, LEAD_ON, LAG_ON, HIGH_ALARM).
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Change 'state' to an enumeration or add separate attributes for each threshold to represent distinct switch states.

domain_model_issues.description: No lowLiquidDepth threshold is provided to stop pumps before the well runs dry (REQ-011, REQ-026).
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Add a 'lowLiquidDepth' attribute to FloatSwitch to represent the minimum operating depth.

domain_model_issues.description: PumpControlUnit provides alarm functionality (REQ-024, REQ-025) but has no direct association to Alarm or Buzzer.
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Create an association from PumpControlUnit to Alarm (and through Alarm to Buzzer and ControlDisplayPanel) to enable alarm activation.

domain_model_issues.description: No class represents environmental sensors despite REQ-014 requiring monitoring of environmental conditions.
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Introduce an EnvironmentalSensor class (or specialized sensor classes) and associate it with WetWellControlSystem.

domain_model_issues.description: Both WetWellControlSystem and PumpControlUnit define similar monitoring methods for liquid level and pump state, leading to overlapping responsibilities.
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Consolidate liquid level and pump state monitoring in one component and have the other reference it to avoid duplication.

domain_model_issues.description: startPumpMotor(pump) does not include logic to select and start an alternative pump when the requested pump is unavailable (REQ-029).
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Add internal selection logic or a helper method (e.g., selectAlternativePump()) to handle unavailability scenarios.

domain_model_issues.description: Alarm.activate() is defined but does not explicitly trigger visual alarms (indicator lights) as required by REQ-004 and REQ-024.
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Ensure Alarm.activate() communicates with ControlDisplayPanel to enable indicator lights or embed visual alarm capability.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The design of the wet well control system shall provide for the safety and protection of pumping station operators, maintenance personnel, and the public from hazards that may result from its operation.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: REQ-001 (Priority: High, Version: 1.0, Type: Safety) The wet well control system shall ensure the safety and protection of pumping station operators, maintenance personnel, and the public from hazards that may result from its operation. Rationale: To comply with OSHA and local safety standards. Source: Safety Standards Document. Status: Draft. Acceptance Criteria: No incidents reported in 12 months; hazard scenarios validated in simulation.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Adding these fields ensures the requirement is traceable, testable, and aligned with safety standards.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The control system shall be responsible for monitoring and reporting the level of liquid in the wet well.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: REQ-002 (Priority: Medium, Version: 1.0, Type: Functional) The wet well control system shall monitor liquid level continuously and report current depth every 5 seconds to the SCADA host. Rationale: Timely data is needed to control pumps. Source: System Specification Doc. Status: Draft. Acceptance Criteria: Level data logged and visible in UI; no data gap exceeding 10 seconds.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Specifying measurement frequency, acceptance criteria and metadata makes this requirement testable and clear.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The control system shall be responsible for monitoring and reporting the state of each pump and whether it is currently running or not.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: REQ-003 (Priority: Medium, Version: 1.0, Type: Functional) The wet well control system shall monitor each pump’s running state and report status changes within 2 seconds to the control display panel. Rationale: Accurate pump status is required for maintenance. Source: Maintenance Handbook. Status: Draft. Acceptance Criteria: Status updates logged and panel indicator changes within 2 seconds.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Defining timing, acceptance criteria and metadata improves clarity and verifiability.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The control system shall activate a visual and audible alarm when a hazardous condition exists.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: REQ-004 (Priority: High, Version: 1.0, Type: Safety) The wet well control system shall activate both visual and audible alarms within 1 second of detecting a hazardous condition (e.g., high water level, unauthorized entry). Rationale: Immediate notification reduces risk. Source: Safety Standards Doc. Status: Draft. Acceptance Criteria: Alarm triggers under each hazard scenario in test bench.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Quantifying timing, hazard types, and acceptance tests ensures requirement is actionable and testable.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The control system shall switch each submersible pump on or off in a timely fashion depending on the level of liquid within the wet well.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: REQ-005 (Priority: High, Version: 1.0, Type: Functional) The wet well control system shall start or stop each submersible pump within 2 seconds of the liquid level crossing configured thresholds. Rationale: Prevent overflow or dry-run. Source: Operational Spec. Status: Draft. Acceptance Criteria: Pump state changes in <2s during level tests; no overflow or dry-run events recorded.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Specifying performance (timeliness), thresholds, and acceptance criteria makes the requirement measurable.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: Each submersible pump shall be equipped with a moisture sensor that detects the occurrence of an external pump seal failure.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: REQ-006 (Priority: Medium, Version: 1.0, Type: Functional) Each submersible pump shall include a moisture sensor capable of detecting external seal failure and reporting detection within 1 second. Rationale: Early leak detection prevents damage. Source: Equipment Spec. Status: Draft. Acceptance Criteria: Sensor triggers alert in controlled leak test.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Adding detection speed, metadata, and acceptance criteria clarifies how the sensor should perform.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: Should a seal failure be detected, the pump shall be turned off and alarm state set.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: REQ-007 (Priority: High, Version: 1.0, Type: Functional) If a seal failure is detected, the wet well control system shall shut off the affected pump within 1 second and activate the alarm. Rationale: Prevent water ingress. Source: Maintenance Spec. Status: Draft. Acceptance Criteria: Leak simulation causes pump shutdown and alarm activation in test bench.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Specifying timing and test criteria makes the requirement verifiable.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The wet well control system shall provide automated operation.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: REQ-008 (Priority: Medium, Version: 1.0, Type: Functional) The wet well control system shall operate pumps automatically based on liquid level thresholds without human intervention. Rationale: Reduce manual errors. Source: Operational Requirements. Status: Draft. Acceptance Criteria: System cycles pumps automatically during level tests.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Defining conditions, acceptance criteria and metadata clarifies what automated operation entails.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The wet well control system shall provide local manual override operation.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: REQ-009 (Priority: Medium, Version: 1.0, Type: Functional) The wet well control system shall allow an on-site operator to manually start and stop pumps via the control display panel. Rationale: Support maintenance activities. Source: User Requirements. Status: Draft. Acceptance Criteria: Manual commands from panel override automatic mode in test.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Specifying interface, acceptance criteria and metadata ensures clarity and testability.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The wet well control system shall provide local observational operation.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: REQ-010 (Priority: Low, Version: 1.0, Type: Functional) The wet well control system shall enable on-site personnel to view real-time pump and level status without altering controls. Rationale: Monitor without risk. Source: User Requirements. Status: Draft. Acceptance Criteria: Display panel shows live data only in observation mode.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Adding operation mode detail, acceptance criteria and metadata improves clarity.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The wet well control system shall start the pump motors to prevent the wet well from running over and stop the pump motors before the wet well runs dry.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: REQ-011 (Priority: High, Version: 1.0, Type: Functional) The wet well control system shall start pumps at the high-level threshold (e.g., 8 ft) and stop pumps at the low-level threshold (e.g., 2 ft) to prevent overflow or dry-run. Rationale: Maintain safe operating range. Source: Level Control Spec. Status: Draft. Acceptance Criteria: Threshold tests verify correct pump actions.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Specifying thresholds and acceptance tests makes requirement precise and testable.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The wet well control system shall keep track of whether or not each motor is running.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: REQ-012 (Priority: Medium, Version: 1.0, Type: Functional) The wet well control system shall log and display each motor’s run state changes within 2 seconds. Rationale: Support diagnostics. Source: Operational Spec. Status: Draft. Acceptance Criteria: State changes recorded and displayed within 2 seconds in test.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Adding performance and acceptance criteria ensures verifiability.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The wet well control system shall monitor the pumping site for unauthorized entry or trespass.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: REQ-013 (Priority: High, Version: 1.0, Type: Security) The wet well control system shall detect unauthorized entry via the access door sensor and report within 1 second. Rationale: Ensure site security. Source: Security Requirements. Status: Draft. Acceptance Criteria: Break-circuit test triggers alarm in <1s.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Specifying security type, timing, and acceptance criteria improves clarity.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The wet well control system shall monitor the environmental conditions within the wet well.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: REQ-014 (Priority: Medium, Version: 1.0, Type: Functional) The wet well control system shall monitor temperature and humidity inside the wet well and report readings every 15 seconds. Rationale: Prevent equipment damage. Source: Environmental Spec. Status: Draft. Acceptance Criteria: Sensor data logged and displayed; no stale data >30s.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Defining monitored parameters, frequency, and acceptance criteria makes the requirement testable.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The wet well control system shall monitor the physical condition of each pump for the existence of moisture and excessive temperatures.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: REQ-015 (Priority: Medium, Version: 1.0, Type: Functional) The wet well control system shall monitor each pump’s moisture sensor and temperature sensor, reporting anomalies within 1 second. Rationale: Early fault detection. Source: Pump Spec. Status: Draft. Acceptance Criteria: Fault simulation triggers report and alarm.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Specifying sensors, timing, and acceptance tests clarifies performance requirements.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The wet well control system shall display real time and historical operational parameters.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: REQ-016 (Priority: Low, Version: 1.0, Type: Functional) The wet well control system shall display current and archived data for liquid level, pump state, and alarms on the control display panel with time stamps. Rationale: Support troubleshooting. Source: UI Spec. Status: Draft. Acceptance Criteria: Data retrieval within 2 seconds for historical queries.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Defining data types and performance criteria makes the requirement measurable.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The wet well control system shall provide an alarm feature.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: REQ-017 (Priority: High, Version: 1.0, Type: Functional) The wet well control system shall include audible and visual alarms for fault and hazard conditions as defined in REQ-004 and REQ-007. requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The control display panel shall have indicator lights for pump running state.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: REQ-018 (Priority: Medium, Version: 1.0, Type: UI) The control display panel shall include green indicator lights that illuminate when each pump is running and turn off when the pump stops. Rationale: Provide clear status. Source: Hardware Spec. Status: Draft. Acceptance Criteria: Light toggles correctly during pump tests.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Specifying color, behavior, and acceptance tests makes the UI requirement verifiable.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The control display panel shall have indicator lights for pump seal failure state.

Rationale: Immediate visual alert. Source: Hardware Spec. Status: Draft. Acceptance Criteria: Light turns on during leak simulation.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Defining color and test criteria ensures the indicator functions as intended.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The control display panel shall have indicator lights for pump high temperature failure state.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: REQ-020 (Priority: Medium, Version: 1.0, Type: UI) The control display panel shall include amber indicator lights that illuminate when a pump motor high-temperature condition is detected. Rationale: Warn of overheating. Source: Hardware Spec. Status: Draft. Acceptance Criteria: Light activates during overheat test.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Specifying color, condition, and tests makes this requirement actionable.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The control display panel shall have indicator lights for high wet well level alarm state.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: REQ-021 (Priority: Medium, Version: 1.0, Type: UI) The control display panel shall include red indicator lights that illuminate when the wet well level exceeds the high-level threshold. Rationale: Alert operator to overflow risk. Source: UI Spec. Status: Draft. Acceptance Criteria: Light turns on during level threshold test.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Adding threshold reference and acceptance tests ensures clarity.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: Indicator lights shall be enabled when an alarm state is activated.

requirement_completeness.rationale: Specifying timing and acceptance criteria makes the behavior measurable.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: A buzzer shall sound when an alarm state is activated.

Rationale: Ensure audible alert. Source: Alarm Spec. Status: Draft. Acceptance Criteria: Measured sound level ≥85 dB in tests.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Defining sound level, timing, and acceptance tests clarifies the audible alarm requirement.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: Monitor and detect prohibited entry to the wet well through the access door by way of broken electrical circuit. Both audible and visible alarms shall be activated.

Rationale: Prevent unauthorized access. Source: Security Spec. Status: Draft. Acceptance Criteria: Circuit break test triggers alarms in <1s.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Including system component, timing, and acceptance criteria improves specificity.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: Monitor and detect occurrence of a pump motor seal leak. If a leak has been detected, both an audible and visible alarm shall be activated.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: REQ-025 (Priority: High, Version: 1.0, Type: Functional) The pump control unit shall detect a seal leak via MoistureSensor and activate audible and visual alarms within 1 second. Rationale: Early fault notification. Source: Maintenance Spec. Status: Draft. Acceptance Criteria: Leak simulation triggers alarms correctly.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Clarifying sensor, timing, and test criteria makes the requirement verifiable.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The pump control unit shall start the submersible pump motors to prevent the wet well from running over and stop the pump motors before the wet well runs dry.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: REQ-026 (Priority: High, Version: 1.0, Type: Functional) The pump control unit shall start pumps at 8 ft and stop at 2 ft to prevent overflow and dry-run. Rationale: Maintain operational safety. Source: Level Control Spec. Status: Draft. Acceptance Criteria: Threshold tests verify correct pump actions.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Specifying thresholds and acceptance criteria makes the requirement precise and testable.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The pump control unit shall keep track of whether or not each motor is running.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: REQ-027 (Priority: Medium, Version: 1.0, Type: Functional) The pump control unit shall log each motor’s run state changes and update the ControlDisplayPanel within 2 seconds. Rationale: Support diagnostics. Source: Operational Spec. Status: Draft. Acceptance Criteria: State changes recorded and displayed within 2 seconds in test.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Adding performance and acceptance criteria ensures verifiability.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The pump control unit shall keep track of whether or not each motor is available to run.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: REQ-028 (Priority: Medium, Version: 1.0, Type: Functional) The pump control unit shall monitor and log each motor’s availability (e.g., power, faults) and report status every 5 seconds. Rationale: Ensure reliable operation. Source: Operational Spec. Status: Draft. Acceptance Criteria: Availability status updates visible in UI during tests.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Defining monitoring frequency and acceptance criteria clarifies expected behavior.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: If a pump motor is not available to run and a request has been made for the pump motor to start, an alternative motor shall be started in its place.

Rationale: Maintain pumping capacity. Source: Redundancy Spec. Status: Draft. Acceptance Criteria: Unavailability simulation triggers alternate pump start in <1s.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Adding timing, fallback logic description, and acceptance criteria improves clarity and testability.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: An alarm state shall be set when the high water level is reached.

Rationale: Prevent overflow. Source: Level Control Spec. Status: Draft. Acceptance Criteria: Level threshold test sets alarm state correctly.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Specifying threshold and acceptance tests makes the requirement precise and verifiable.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The starting and stopping of the pump motors shall be done in a manner that equalizes the run times on the motors.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: Level switches shall be used to indicate when pump motors should be started.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The pump control unit shall be notified if excess moisture is detected in a pump motor.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: REQ-033 (Priority: Medium, Version: 1.0, Type: Functional) MoistureSensor shall notify the pump control unit within 1 second of detecting external seal moisture. requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The pump control unit shall be notified if a pump motor overheats and shall shut down the overheated motor.

Rationale: Prevent overflow. Source: Level Control Spec. Status: Draft. Acceptance Criteria: Threshold test sets alarm state in <1s.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Specifying threshold, timing, and acceptance tests ensures clarity and verifiability.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The wet well control system shall equalize the run time between the pumps.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: REQ-043 (Priority: Low, Version: 1.0, Type: Functional) The wet well control system shall alternate pump lead/lag roles to equalize cumulative pump run times within 5% over any 30-day period. Rationale: Extend pump life. Source: Pump Maintenance Spec. Status: Draft. Acceptance Criteria: Run-time logs show ≤5% imbalance after 30 days.

reasoning.domain_model: I merged all core classes, resolved naming conflicts, and separated high-level coordination (WetWellControlSystem) from detailed pump control (PumpControlUnit). I unified SubmersiblePump and Pump into one Pump class, combined sensor classes with consistent attributes, and consolidated alarm components by keeping both Alarm and Buzzer with a composition relationship. I incorporated float-switch thresholds and states, and I refined relationships to reflect clear ownership and associations, producing a coherent, complete, and consistent domain model.
reasoning.analysis:
Analysis aggregated using openai with specialized component processing:
- requirement_completeness: We reviewed both the deepseek and openai assessments for each requirement. For each item, we preserved the lowest completeness score (30.0), combined all missing elements (they were identical across sources), and retained the detailed suggested improvements and rationales. This conservative approach ensures no optimistic scoring and full coverage of missing metadata, performance, and acceptance criteria insights from both analyses.
- requirement_issues: For each requirement, issues from the deepseek and openai analyses were aggregated and duplicates merged. When both sources flagged the same concern, we combined descriptions, adopted the more severe severity, and unified suggested fixes. Unique issues from either source were preserved. Conflicts between system components were grouped under Conflict, overlapping or redundant requirements under Inconsistency, and lacking details under Ambiguity or Missing Context. The final list is sorted by requirement ID, with consolidated issue entries and comprehensive suggested fixes.
- missing_requirements: Both source analyses contained identical sets of missing requirements (MR1 through MR25). We compared each entry and found no material differences, so we merged the duplicate lists into a single comprehensive list, preserving the most detailed information from the deepseek analysis, assigning unique IDs, and including full descriptions, suggested requirements, affected model elements, and rationales for each requirement.
- domain_model_issues: Aggregated issues from both sources and preserved all unique items. Merged duplicate ControlDisplayPanel issues by choosing the higher severity and combining descriptions and fixes. Retained source distinctions for relationships and methods. Included all attribute, class, relationship, method, and general consistency issues, ensuring each has clear descriptions, severities, and suggested fixes aligned with requirements.
